<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<worksheet>
  <title>Review 01- Limits of a Function</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      <alert>Instructions:</alert> Prepare neatly written solutions to the following problems. 
      Show all relevant work and use proper notation/terminology. 
      <!--Submit these problems as a single PDF. Be sure your file is readable before submitting! -->
      Calculators should NOT be used.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <page>
    <exercise>
  <title>Limit Laws Evaluation</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Suppose <m>\lim_{x \to 1} f(x) = 2</m> and <m>\lim_{x \to 1} g(x) = -1</m>. Find
      <me>\lim_{x \to 1} \left( \frac{2f(x)}{3g(x) + 1} + f(x) \right)</me>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      Using the limit laws for sums, quotients, and scalar multiples:
      <md>
        <mrow>\lim_{x \to 1} \left( \frac{2f(x)}{3g(x) + 1} + f(x) \right) \amp = \frac{2 \lim_{x \to 1} f(x)}{3 \lim_{x \to 1} g(x) + 1} + \lim_{x \to 1} f(x)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{2(2)}{3(-1) + 1} + 2</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{4}{-2} + 2 = -2 + 2 = 0</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
  <title>Rationalizing Limits</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Find <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \to 1} \frac{x - 1}{\sqrt{x} - 1}</m>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      Direct substitution results in the indeterminate form <m>0/0</m>. We rationalize the denominator:
      <md>
        <mrow>\lim_{x \to 1} \frac{x - 1}{\sqrt{x} - 1} \cdot \frac{\sqrt{x} + 1}{\sqrt{x} + 1} \amp = \lim_{x \to 1} \frac{(x - 1)(\sqrt{x} + 1)}{x - 1}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \lim_{x \to 1} (\sqrt{x} + 1)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{1} + 1 = 2</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
  <title>Composition and Domain</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>f(x) = \sqrt{x}</m> and <m>g(x) = x^2 - 1</m>, find <m>(f \circ g)(x)</m> and its domain.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      The composition is:
      <me>(f \circ g)(x) = f(g(x)) = \sqrt{x^2 - 1}</me>
      For the domain, we require the radicand to be non-negative:
      <me>x^2 - 1 \ge 0 \implies x^2 \ge 1 \implies |x| \ge 1</me>
      The domain in interval notation is <m>(-\infty, -1] \cup [1, \infty)</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
  <title>Trigonometric Limits at Infinity</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Find <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \to \infty} x \sin\left(\frac{1}{x}\right)</m>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      Let <m>t = 1/x</m>. As <m>x \to \infty</m>, <m>t \to 0^+</m>.
      The limit becomes:
      <me>\lim_{t \to 0^+} \frac{1}{t} \sin(t) = \lim_{t \to 0^+} \frac{\sin(t)}{t}</me>
      Using the fundamental trigonometric limit, the result is <m>1</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

  </page>


</worksheet>
